<font color="#FF0000">TEACHING ABOUT VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar  1 10:33:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Reply to Gerald Ney: As we study Viet Nam in my course we look at Viet Nam in context of how policy makers made decisions an read from Loren Baritz, BACKFIRE. In addition, students read Mark Backer's NAM. These additional readings help students see how normal people, people like themselves can be transformed to do things they would normally consider wrong, even if it is the controlled use of violence. My Lai is simply an extreme example of the more general process, a place where it goes wrong. The PBS Frontline program on My Lai makes your point very well, and indeed the whole class I teach attempts to make your point in a wide variety of contexts. It is my feeling, based on 25 years of studyingviolence in awuied variety of contexts, that only by confronting the potential in us all, and seeing our commonality wioth those who use violence, can we move toward &quot;peace making&quot; ways of living BEFORE and instead of using violenec. Thanks for your observations.<br><br>

